===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|pece|pece, peas, pees|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|pais||peace|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term/t|la|pāx||peace}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*paḱ-||to fasten, stick, place}}, related to Latin {{term/t|la|pacīscor||agree, stipulate}}, Latin {{term/t|la|pangō||fasten, fix}}; see [[pact]]. Displaced native [[Middle English]] {{term|frith|lang=enm}}, {{term|frede||peace|lang=enm}} (from [[Old English]] {{term|friþ|lang=ang}}, {{term/t|ang|frēod||peace}}), Middle English {{term|sib|sib, sibbe|peace|lang=enm}} (from Old English {{term|sibb||peace, kinship|lang=ang}}), Middle English {{term|grith||peace, security|lang=enm}} (from [[Old English]] {{term|griþ|lang=ang}} and Old Norse {{term|grið||lang=non}}), Middle English {{term|saught|saht, saught|peace, reconciliation|lang=enm}} (from Old English {{term|seht|lang=ang}}, {{term|sæht||peace, pact, agreement|lang=ang}}).

